      • accept

        public <A,T extends Throwable> A accept(ASTVisitor<A,T> visitor)
         throws T extends Throwable
        Description copied from interface: AST
        The accept method as per the visitor pattern, allowing us to visit different kinds of AST nodes. Type variable A stands for whatever the visitor returns on this AST node (see ASTVisitor for details). The overall annotation on accept thus states that this will return whatever the visitor returns. Type variable T stands for whatever kind of exception the visitor returns. The clause extends Throwable is necessary to indicate that T must be an exception of some kind; without this clause, we could not say throws T without having a type error. By parameterizing T (as opposed to saying this throws, say, a TokenizerException), accept can throw whatever exception is most appropriate for the provided visitor. The parser takes advantage of this by using this to throw ParserException, which AST need not know about.
        Specified by:
        accept in interface AST
        Parameters:
        visitor - The visitor to accept, as per the visitor pattern
        Returns:
        Whatever the visitor dictates to return (see the ASTVisitor definition)
        Throws:
        T - Whatever the visitor has declared to throw, under conditions which are specific to the particular visitor being used.
        T extends Throwable
